<HEADLINE>
<P>
MURDER CASE DEFENDANT FREED AFTER HUNG JURIES; COURTS: MARTIAL ARTS INSTRUCTOR 
WAS TRIED TWICE IN A CO-WORKER'S DEATH. 'HE'S PROBABLY GUILTY,' THE JUDGE SAYS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARK SABBATINI, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A martial arts instructor tried twice for allegedly killing a female co-worker 
was set free Tuesday by a judge who said the man is "probably guilty" but 
expressed doubt that a verdict could ever be reached in the case. 
</P>
<P>
 Both trials of Stuart Edward Milburn, who has been in custody without bail 
since his arrest in March, ended in hung juries. 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles Superior Court Judge Charles Horan, who presided over the trials, 
granted a defense motion requesting that a third trial not be held on the 
current evidence. 
</P>
<P>
 "The inescapable fact is we could try the case five times and we would have 
five hung juries unless something new happens," Horan said in making his 
ruling. 
</P>
<P>
 The judge said that the evidence presented during the trials strongly 
implicates Milburn in the slaying of a Canyon Country woman who was a rising 
star in the martial arts world, but that it is not enough to eliminate all 
reasonable doubt. 
</P>
<P>
 "He's probably guilty," the judge commented from the bench. "I'm not going to 
try to comfort him or his family by suggesting otherwise." 
</P>
<P>
 The prosecution claimed that Milburn, 27, killed Veronica Estrada, 29, because 
he was jealous of her professional achievements, including being named 
instructor of the year instead of him at the martial arts studio where they 
worked. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 But the prosecution's efforts were hampered by eyewitnesses who gave uncertain 
identifications of Milburn at the murder scene and by tests showing that none 
of the blood found there matched the defendant's. In addition, a defense 
witness testified that she saw Milburn at the studio at the time of the murder, 
which was committed elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
 Milburn's attorney, Darryl Mounger, declined to make his client available for 
interviews after the ruling. The defendant's father, Stuart H. Milburn, 
appeared angry with the judge's comments but relieved that his son was set 
free. 
</P>
<P>
 "I disagree entirely with the judge," the elder Milburn said. "I'm just 
disappointed it's taken so long for this." 
</P>
<P>
 Milburn was accused of murdering Estrada last December as she walked along a 
dark road toward her home. Jurors voted 8-4 to convict Milburn during his first 
trial, which ended in September. His second trial ended Dec. 7 with jurors 
voting 7-5 for acquittal. 
</P>
<P>
 The case against him remains open and he could still be retried. 
</P>
<P>
 Milburn showed no emotion during the ruling. Estrada's family and friends also 
listened silently, but many were in tears afterward. 
</P>
<P>
 "She was my friend and I think he did it and in my heart I hate him for it," 
said Renee Flapper, who was also a friend of Milburn. "I don't know what to 
think. I wasn't expecting this." 
</P>
<P>
 The prosecutor, Deputy Dist. Atty. Robert Foltz, said he was not surprised at 
the judge's ruling. 
</P>
<P>
 "I feel the court, with what they had to deal with, acted very appropriately," 
Foltz said. 
</P>
<P>
 The judge's statement about the guilt of the accused was highly unusual for a 
criminal trial, said Robert Pugsley, a professor of criminal law at 
Southwestern University Law School in Los Angeles. Pugsley said that the judge 
may have been venting "humanly understandable frustrations" about the case, but 
that the comments could prejudice further proceedings against Milburn. 
</P>
<P>
 "In effect, it's putting the D.A. on notice in a very public way that if he 
doesn't come up with more . . . he should not bring (the case) against 
(Milburn) next time," Pugsley said. 
</P>
<P>
 If there were a third trial, Pugsley added, Horan almost certainly would not 
be able to preside over it because of his remarks. 
</P>
<P>
 On "every evidentiary ruling where he ruled favorable to the prosecution, the 
defense would make an objection of bias," Pugsley said. 
</P>
<P>
 Estrada was the American Taekwondo Assn.'s top-ranked female competitor in the 
second-degree black-belt division. She was strangled about 8:15 p.m. Dec. 15, 
1993, and her partially clothed body was found the next morning in bushes along 
Soledad Canyon Road. 
</P>
<P>
 Prosecutor Foltz said he is not giving up yet, however. "There's someone out 
there who knows something," he said after the hearing. 
</P>
<P>
 Jurors in the first trial said that at one point they voted 10-2 to convict 
Milburn, but eventually deadlocked 8-4 for conviction after four weeks of 
deliberation because of the uncertain evidence against him. The second trial 
ended in a mistrial after five days of deliberation, with jurors declining to 
comment on the reasons for their deadlock. 
</P>
<P>
 Horan said the defense made a mistake by putting Milburn on the stand during 
the first trial. Milburn came off as "arrogant," the judge said, and unable to 
answer key prosecution questions. 
</P>
<P>
 "The jury didn't like him very much," Horan said. 
</P>
<P>
 Estrada's family has criticized the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department's 
handling of the case, stating that delays were caused when the original 
detectives were replaced several days after the murder. In addition, some of 
Estrada's clothing from the murder scene was destroyed by the coroner's office 
on orders mistakenly given by a sheriff's lieutenant. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think that was one of the biggest mistakes ever made by the Sheriff's 
Department," said Estrada's father, Robert, after Tuesday's court hearing. 
</P>
<P>
 But Foltz said he doesn't know if the destroyed clothing would have had a 
significant impact on the case because a coroner's official testified that 
there was no blood or other incriminating evidence on the items. 
</P>
<P>
 Estrada's sister, Theresa, said she would never be at peace if her sister's 
murder remained unsolved. But she was not hopeful. 
</P>
<P>
 "What are they going to come up with that they haven't already?" she asked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
